So what are some common pitfalls that I've seen? Well, a common pitfall that I've often

00:06:06.640 --> 00:06:12.160
seen stems from hard-coded secrets. So they're not great from a security perspective, especially

00:06:12.160 --> 00:06:17.359
if you're putting code into something like a Git repository. If you imagine something

00:06:17.359 --> 00:06:21.440
like a database password being put into source codes, then you need to remember to remove

00:06:21.440 --> 00:06:26.679
the secrets and then add them back in. It could be an extra step that's sometimes forgotten.

00:06:26.679 --> 00:06:31.440
So this is an example database connection with some credentials that might be used for

00:06:31.440 --> 00:06:37.739
developing locally, and this might be what's required when you actually deploy. So unless

00:06:37.739 --> 00:06:42.239
you change the codes between each environment, you're going to get database connection issues.

00:06:42.239 --> 00:06:46.640
While this is bad from a security perspective and involves some extra effort, it doesn't

00:06:46.640 --> 00:06:50.459
necessarily cause deployments to fail, it's just, yeah, when you forget to change them

00:06:50.459 --> 00:06:54.160
between the two. So I'm going to go into some niche European

