are configured. So basically the right-hand side headlight is dipped so that you don't

00:07:04.260 --> 00:07:09.820
blind everyone in the oncoming lane. Now the rest of Europe drives on the right. I don't

00:07:09.820 --> 00:07:15.260
know why these pictures are oriented this way. I wish they were just the same way. Slightly

00:07:15.260 --> 00:07:21.859
annoying, but that's where we are. As you might expect, the lights are the opposite

00:07:21.859 --> 00:07:27.339
way around in the rest of Europe. So driving a UK car in, say, France without adjusting

00:07:27.339 --> 00:07:31.739
your headlights is illegal, because you would be blinding everyone. Some fancier cars have

00:07:31.739 --> 00:07:35.660
the functionality to switch the configuration at the press of a switch, and some other cars

00:07:35.660 --> 00:07:39.940
didn't have that functionality, and that meant they couldn't easily adapt when you, say,

00:07:39.940 --> 00:07:46.220
went to France or something like that. So hard-coded variables kind of limit the configurability

00:07:46.220 --> 00:07:52.739
at deployment time. To get this sort of European, UK car headlight switching capability, you

00:07:52.739 --> 00:07:59.420
can do this with your code. Replace your variables with calls to environment variables. Now,

00:07:59.420 --> 00:08:05.220
this code could be committed to a Git repository and you won't be showing any sensitive values,

00:08:05.220 --> 00:08:09.220
and yeah, you'd have to change the code between your dev and broad environment. So you might

00:08:09.220 --> 00:08:16.579
be thinking, where do you actually set the values if not in the code? Well, here's PositConnect.

00:08:16.579 --> 00:08:20.899
It's a little bit small, but the section I want to point out is on the right‑hand side,

00:08:20.899 --> 00:08:27.660
and this is this Vars tab, and this is the section for setting environment variables,

00:08:27.660 --> 00:08:31.420
and here at the bottom, we already have our environment variables already set. We've got

00:08:31.420 --> 00:08:37.539
the names of the environment variables that were in the code. When I click edit, I can

00:08:37.539 --> 00:08:41.580
only set a new variable. It doesn't show the old value. The variables are stored securely

00:08:41.580 --> 00:08:49.619
from other users of the platform. So this in particular is good for things like personal

00:08:49.619 --> 00:08:57.539
API keys and the like. Now, with ShinyApps.io and ShinyServer, it's

00:08:57.539 --> 00:09:02.260
not quite as swish. You need to have this .R environment file in your app directory

00:09:02.260 --> 00:09:10.219
to set the environment variables. So environment variables, like this point on environment

00:09:10.219 --> 00:09:14.419
variables, kind of leads me nicely into my next point, which is more the recourse to

00:09:14.419 --> 00:09:20.260
this actual problem, which is the availability of external resources. So just as cars need

00:09:20.260 --> 00:09:28.099
fuel to run, your app probably relies on external data. So your app might rely on APIs that

00:09:28.099 --> 00:09:34.580
allow external systems to communicate and interact with your Shiny app. You might pull

00:09:34.580 --> 00:09:39.900
data from a database to populate some nice visualizations. Similarly, you might pull

00:09:39.900 --> 00:09:45.859
resources from some sort of remote file or something like that. If these resources aren't

00:09:45.859 --> 00:09:50.500
available, then it's kind of like your app's fuel source isn't available. So some common

00:09:50.500 --> 00:09:56.940
causes for this are things like incorrect credentials, which I've just covered. It could

00:09:56.940 --> 00:10:02.820
also be things like connectivity and things like firewall rules. For example, with ShinyApps.io,

00:10:02.820 --> 00:10:08.580
in order to access a database that's behind something like a company firewall, you need

00:10:08.580 --> 00:10:14.900
to whitelist some ShinyApps.io addresses in the firewall, and you need to ask a sysadmin

00:10:14.900 --> 00:10:22.659
or someone who is in charge of that. Another thing I've come across is permissions

00:10:22.659 --> 00:10:30.299
of the user in the database. So you want to ensure that your database user that's specified

00:10:30.299 --> 00:10:35.539
in the Shiny application has the necessary permissions to perform the operations. These

00:10:35.539 --> 00:10:39.979
might be read-only, and if you try and do a write operation in your Shiny app, then

00:10:39.979 --> 00:10:46.099
obviously that's not going to work. The next reason apps fail to deploy is probably the

00:10:46.099 --> 00:10:49.979
most common, and it's issues with dependencies. So libraries, packages, and files that make

00:10:49.979 --> 00:10:55.979
up your application. Just as there's a bunch of parts that fit together to make up a car,

00:10:55.979 --> 00:11:00.099
it's crucial to ensure that you have a clear understanding of the dependencies that your

00:11:00.099 --> 00:11:06.940
app requires, and that they're included in the deployment process. So maintaining this

00:11:06.940 --> 00:11:13.140
slight detail car parts list, it's kind of like what it's like, and if something's missing

00:11:13.140 --> 00:11:17.419
and someone wants to build a car from that car parts list, and something's missing, then

00:11:17.419 --> 00:11:23.099
the car's probably not going to work. The RxConnect package and write manifest function

00:11:23.099 --> 00:11:27.599
can be pretty helpful with maintaining things like this, so it's great for R package dependencies

00:11:27.599 --> 00:11:33.140
and files, but it doesn't help when they rely on things like underlying system dependencies.

00:11:33.140 --> 00:11:39.380
So many R packages contain code written in C or C++ for performance reasons, so if you

00:11:39.380 --> 00:11:45.380
use these, you need to have the development tools installed on your deployment environment.

00:11:45.380 --> 00:11:53.299
Certain packages might need system utilities, such as wget, curl, or git to download data

